          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " specified."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Handling Responses and Error Codes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Successful responses return HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "audio_url",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " or "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "audio_data",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Common errors include HTTP 429 for rate limiting, HTTP 400 for invalid parameters (e.g., unsupported "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "voice_id",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), and HTTP 503 for service unavailability. Implement logging for error codes and use the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "X-Request-ID",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " header for tracing. For production, set up monitoring to alert on error rates exceeding 1% and cache frequent voice profiles to reduce latency."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimizing for Latency and Throughput"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To minimize latency, pre-warm the API by sending a health check request during application startup. Use connection pooling and keep-alive headers to reuse TCP connections. For high-throughput scenarios, batch multiple synthesis requests asynchronously using a queue system like RabbitMQ or Kafka. Adjust the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "sample_rate",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter based on use case—lower rates (e.g., 8000 Hz) reduce bandwidth for telephony, while higher rates (e.g., 24000 Hz) enhance quality for media applications. Profile memory usage when handling large audio files to avoid bottlenecks."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
